{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17595627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17595627"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:06:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:06:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15372"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15372"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.11,0.07,0.57,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8063"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63806"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8063"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15372"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49236"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19574"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19576"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20890"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63806"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETumour markers are substances found in blood, urine or body tissues that can be elevated in various cancers. While they can be useful for monitoring disease progression and treatment response, their utility for initial diagnosis may be limited.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most commonly used tumour marker for monitoring pancreatic adenocarcinoma?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alpha-fetoprotein","Carcinoembryonic antigen","CA 15-3","CA 19-9","CA 125"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECA 19-9\u003C/strong\u003E is the most widely used tumour marker for pancreatic adenocarcinoma, although it has limitations including false positives in benign pancreatic and hepatobiliary conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECA 19-9 has a sensitivity of 70-90% and specificity of 68-91% for pancreatic cancer. The marker may also be elevated in other gastrointestinal cancers and non-malignant conditions such as pancreatitis, making it unsuitable as a diagnostic test. However, it is useful for monitoring disease progression and treatment response in known pancreatic cancer cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlpha-fetoprotein\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used as a tumour marker for hepatocellular carcinoma and germ cell tumours.  \u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoembryonic antigen\u003C/strong\u003E is mainly used in colorectal cancer monitoring. \u003Cstrong\u003ECA 125\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily associated with ovarian cancer. \u003Cstrong\u003ECA 15-3\u003C/strong\u003E is used in breast cancer to monitor response to treatment or recurrence.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["CA 19-9 is the primary tumour marker used for monitoring pancreatic adenocarcinoma"],"references":["Kuhn E, Morbini P, Cancellieri A, Damiani S, Cavazza A, Comin CE. Adenocarcinoma classification: patterns and prognosis. Pathologica. 2018 Mar;110(1):5-11. PMID: 30259909","Podolsky, D. K., Camilleri, M., Fitz, J. G., Kalloo, A. N., Shanahan, F., \u0026 Wang, T. C. (Eds.). (2015). Yamada\u0027s textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49236"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15372"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49236"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T17:08:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-22T17:09:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8063"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63806"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:24+10:30"},"relation